	<div class="post">
	
        <div class="posttype">
        	<a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/tumblog/articles/" title=""><img src="http://gamifyforthewin.com/wp-content/themes/elefolio/images/ico-text.png" alt="" /></a>
        </div><!-- /.posttype -->
	    
	    	    <h2 class="title"><a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/2011/08/01/getting-into-the-game-2/" rel="bookmark" title="Getting Into the Game">Getting Into the Game</a></h2>
	    	    
	    <p class="post-meta">
    <span class="post-author"><span class="small">by</span> <a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/author/kevin-werbach/" title="Posts by Kevin Werbach" rel="author">Kevin Werbach</a></span>
    <span class="post-date"><span class="small">on</span> August 1, 2011</span>
    <span class="post-category"><span class="small">in</span> <a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/category/gamification/" rel="category tag">Gamification</a>, <a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/category/symposium/" rel="category tag">Symposium</a></span>
    </p>
	    
	    <div class="entry">
			<p>Welcome to <strong>For the Win</strong>, a new project for the serious study of gamification.</p>
<p>We describe gamification as the use of mechanisms from games in non-game contexts.  That&#8217;s pretty broad, encompassing everything from points and leaderboards on consumer-oriented websites to government-funded prizes to produce disruptive innovations.  However you define it, there is a great deal of activity around gamification today.  Big claims are being made, venture-funded startups are signing customers, and some real success stories are cropping up.  We believe it&#8217;s time to bring together the various communities of gamification practitioners and the various communities of researchers who study it. We&#8217;re convinced the academics have something to add to the conversation, and so do the companies, consultants, public interest groups, and government actors.</p>
<p>The organizers are <a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/participants/#KevinWerbach">Kevin Werbach</a>, a professor of Legal Studies at the Wharton School of the University of Pennsylvania, and <a href="http://gamifyforthewin.com/participants/#DanHunter">Dan Hunter</a>, a professor at New York Law School.  We&#8217;ve both had a long-standing interest in games, and in technologies that change nature of business and life.  We believe that, at a minimum, gamification will become a recognized business practice in areas such as marketing, HR, and innovation.  And it has the potential to be much more than that.  We will be teaching the first-ever MBA course on gamification this fall.  <strong>For the Win</strong> will house our various efforts in this emerging field.</p>
<p>Our first activity is a symposium on August 8-9, at the Wharton School in Philadelphia.  We have been fortunate to attract a large number of the most thoughtful and recognized experts in the space.  The event is by invitation to ensure focused discussion, but we will be posting blog reports and video from the event here.</p>
<p>Going forward, we hope <strong>For the Win </strong>will become a valuable resource for information and discussion about gamification.   Please join our social media feeds, available on this page, and contribute to the conversation on the blog.</p>
		</div>
	         
